\begin{doublespace}

\section{Introduction}
\end{doublespace}

\begin{doublespace}
The tradeoff between risk and return is the fundamental principle
of the investment process. Although choosing individual investment
opportunities is important, the top-down analysis of the entire investment
portfolio is crucial for maintaining and updating investment goals.
The decision of how to allocate capital to a few select asset classes
is a very important investment decision; the asset allocation has
been shown to influence almost 80\% of  portfolio returns. 

Traditional mean-variance asset allocation frameworks use a normal
distribution to model returns and variance as a risk measure. While
these traditional methods for understanding risk and return have come
under fire in the recent financial turmoil, research in alternative
models is a growing and promising field. Recent research focuses on
other risk measures for capturing downside risk and different probability
distributions to account for extreme events. We are interested in
building upon the recent research in asset allocation models by investigating
how portfolio rebalancing can be included. 

The central assumption to asset allocation research and implementation
is that investors can reasonably model future market behavior using
historical data and past events. The historical return data are fit
to probability distributions and correlations are used to understand
how asset classes behave together. The normal distribution has been
popular because of the simplicity of obtaining an analytical solution
to the variance minimization and mean return maximization problems.
The assumption that future returns will follow the same distribution
as historical data allows the simulation of future returns. Our research
aims to utilize other distributions and joint distributions that better
account for extreme events in novel asset allocation frameworks. 

The minimization of risk is required in the asset allocation process.
Variance may not be the best risk measure to account for downside
risk since it is a measure of upside and downside volatility. Recent
research has utilized other risk measures instead of variance to better
account for downside risk. The minimization of these new risk measures
has been proven theoretically and demonstrated using simulations. 

Our research goal is to build off of the recent advances in asset
allocation research by developing a rebalancing framework. We will
investigate how using non-normal probability distributions along with
downside risk measures perform in a rebalancing asset allocation optimization
problem.

In this paper, we will first present the previous literature and the
theoretical framework for each concept used in current asset allocation
research. Next, we will describe our methods and implementation of
the different parts of the asset allocation models. We will then end
with our results and discussion.
\end{doublespace}

\begin{doublespace}

\section{Theoretical Framework and Literature Review}
\end{doublespace}

\begin{doublespace}
Markowitz (1952) pioneered the use of mean-variance optimization to
understand the tradeoff between risk and return for a portfolio of
risky assets. Markowitz assumed asset returns are normally distributed,
allowing for an analytical solution to the minimization of variance
and the maximization of expected return. The elegant analytical solution
of this optimization problem is a set of portfolios along the efficient
frontier that represents the best possible returns for each level
of variance. Markowitz set the foundation for asset allocation research
and understanding the tradeoff between risk and return in a portfolio
of risky assets.

The assumptions of normality and variance as a risk measure in asset
allocation have come under pressure since the groundbreaking work
of Markowitz's portfolio theory in light of the market crises in the
past two decades. Research in the past decade has focused on accommodating
the occurrence of extreme events and more relevant measures of risk
besides variance. The application of this research utilizes simulation
data to understand the tradeoff between risk and return with computer
optimization techniques. Our research aims to further develop the
mean-CVaR framework along with the t-Copula probability distribution
to incorporate portfolio rebalancing and to compare these strategies
against traditional mean-variance frameworks. 

In traditional mean-variance portfolio optimization frameworks, Monte
Carlo simulations are run from a Gaussian (normal) joint distribution
for a basket of asset classes. The shortfall of this method is the
thinness of the tail, implying a very low likelihood for situations
where all asset classes are falling significantly in market crash
scenarios. The advantage of using a t-copula is that it can accommodate
higher probabilities of joint events (crashes or bubbles). A copula
combines marginal cumulative distribution functions (CDF) and historical
data of each asset class to create a best fit joint multivariate distribution.
A Gaussian copula assumes a multivariate normal distribution whereas
a t-copula utilizes a multivariate Student\textquoteright{}s t-distribution,
allowing for fatter tails. The t-copula provides a more accurate representation
of real world financial markets and the probability of extreme events
(Demarta and McNeil, 2004). 

Another problem with the mean-variance optimization framework is that
it assumes underlying returns are uncorrelated across time (Fisher,
1994). This is clearly not the case, as higher returns in one period
may lead to equally higher returns the next period because of high
expectations of market trends. To correct for this auto-correlation
between period-to-period returns and to establish the independence
of single-period returns, we used the well-known Fisher-Geltner-Webb's
{}``unsmoothing'' methodology. 

Variance provides a mathematically simple measure of risk for asset
allocation, but it is insufficient as a measure of downside risk.
Variance symmetrically accounts for both upside risk and downside
risk since it is simply a measure of the sample\textquoteright{}s
average squared deviation from the arithmetic mean. When investment
managers assess risk, they are typically more concerned with downside
risk or losses and view upside risk (which may be referred to as \textquotedblleft{}excess
return\textquotedblright{}) favorably. Value-at-risk (VaR) has been
incorporated as another risk measure that aims to better account for
downside risk than variance. VaR is the minimum expected loss at a
certain confidence level (typically 5\%) and can be calculated by
taking the value of the return at the specified (5\%) boundary of
a probability density function (PDF) of return data (either historical
or simulated). Although VaR better accounts for downside risk than
variance does, it fails to capture the extent of the possible losses
beyond the specified (5\%) cutoff. It is possible to have two PDF\textquoteright{}s
with the same VaR (loss associated with the cutoff of 5\%) but one
with a fatter tail and greater losses to the left of the specified
(5\%) cutoff. 

Conditional value-at-risk (CVaR) attempts to rectify this problem:
it is the expected loss given a negative outcome that is greater than
the VaR level, and it can be calculated as a weighted average of the
worst case losses (Agrawal, 2008). Formally, let X be a random variable
denoting a portfolio's loss and $VaR_{\alpha}(X)$ be the VaR at the
$100(1-\alpha)\%$ confidence level. Then $CVaR_{a}(X)$ is defined
as:

\[
CVaR_{\alpha}(X)=E[X|X\text{\ensuremath{\ge}}Var_{\alpha}(X)]\]


Furthermore, CVaR is a more reliable risk measure than VaR under non-normal
and non-continuous probability distributions because it is a \textquotedblleft{}coherent
risk measure\textquotedblright{} and is \textquotedblleft{}sub-additive
and convex\textquotedblright{} (p. 3, Krohmal, Palmquist, and Uryasev,
2002). This means that the CVaR of a portfolio is always less than
or equal to the sum of the CVaR of the weights of the individual asset
classes; furthermore, it can be extended from continuous probability
distributions to discrete scenarios, allowing for optimization using
simulations or discrete distributions and eliminating anomalous results
such as multiple local minima. 

Rockafellar and Uryasev (1999) demonstrate the use of CVaR in an asset
allocation framework and the ability to optimize CVaR using linear
programming methods. The ability to use linear programming stems from
the way CVaR is calculated. Theoretically, CVaR is simply the average
value beyond the specified cutoff (5\%) calculated using the calculus
of integrals. Rockafellar and Uryasev demonstrate that the use of
simulations and a summation to estimate the theoretical CVaR can be
exploited to find the minimum CVaR. The minimization of CVaR in most
situations also provides a minimum VaR because CVaR is always greater
than VaR. Only in situations of extreme skewness does the minimum
VaR differ greatly from the minimum CVaR. Rockafellar and Uryasev
demonstrate the theoretical and mathematical possibility of optimizing
CVaR for portfolio asset allocation. 

Sheikh and Qiao (2009) provide a real world application and verification
of the use of fat tail distributions and CVaR as a risk measure in
an asset allocation framework. They demonstrate that a fat tail distribution
better describes the real world market environment than a normal distribution
by showing that the Student\textquoteright{}s t-copula more closely
fits the historical data, especially the extreme events, than does
the normal copula. The paper also briefly touches on CVaR as a risk
measure that better accounts for downside risk than variance. The
paper then looks at asset allocation using CVaR as a risk measure.
It shows that the use of a Student\textquoteright{}s t-copula assumption
provides a lower downside risk (through lower CVaR) than does the
use of a normal copula. Our research will focus on  a continuation
of this asset allocation model with rebalancing. We will also look
at the historical accuracy and advantage of using our asset allocation
model in comparison to the traditional mean-variance asset allocation
framework. 

So far, we have discussed methods for single period buy and hold portfolio
optimization using CVaR as a risk measure and t-Copula as a joint
probability distribution. Realistically, as certain assets outperform
others, the asset allocation changes endogenously as well. Recent
research considers expanding the optimization to incorporate multiple
period rebalancing using the mean-variance framework as well as the
mean-CVaR framework. 

Master (2003) offers a simple rebalancing strategy, which involves
setting a target allocation. The investor only rebalances when the
allocation deviates beyond a set of trigger points. For instance,
if the trigger point is 3\% for all asset classes, then an investor
only rebalances when the weight for any asset class deviates more
than 3\% from the target weight. This is also known as a tolerance
band rebalancing strategy. According to Master, any rebalancing strategy
should incorporate some basic assumptions. The benefit of rebalancing
is inversely proportional to an investor's risk preference: if an
investor is risk tolerant, meaning he is willing to endure higher
risk for higher potential returns, then his tolerance band will be
wider, meaning he will rebalance less often. It should also be noted
that the benefit of rebalancing rises geometrically. For example,
rebalancing at a deviation of 6\% from the target allocation provides
up to four times as much benefit as rebalancing at deviation of 3\%
of target allocation. The key benefit of rebalancing is to reduce
the tracking error. Mathematically this can be represented as $\text{Rebalancing Benefit }=\frac{{\text{Tracking Error}^{2}\cdot\delta^{2}}}{2\cdot\text{Risk Tolerance}}$
where $\delta$ is the deviation from the target allocation and Tracking
Error represents how closely a portfolio follows the target allocation
to which it is benchmarked. The process of rebalancing involves the
movement of capital across asset classes and incurs costs. While the
benefit of rebalancing rises geometrically, the transaction costs
of rebalancing are linear: selling twice as much of an asset would
cost twice as much. The net benefit of rebalancing is the difference
between the benefit of rebalancing and the cost of rebalancing. 

Sun (2006) extends the concepts of Master\textquoteright{}s research
to incorporate dynamic programming to minimize the cost of rebalancing.
Sun applies the idea to CAPM models, which use mean and variance as
the primary portfolio statistics of interest. The optimal strategy
is to rebalance only when the expected cost of trading is less than
the expected cost of doing nothing. His conclusion is that periodic
or tolerance band rebalancing provides suboptimal rebalanced portfolios.
However, by treating the rebalancing problem as an optimization problem
and solving it using dynamic programming, Sun was able to reduce overall
costs of portfolio rebalancing. 

Guastaroba (2009) applies rebalancing strategies to a portfolio optimization
model that uses Conditional Value at Risk (CVaR) as the risk measure.
The model incorporates rebalancing as a set of linear programming
constraints. He introduces a decision variable to determine whether
to rebalance based on how much the portfolio allocation deviates from
a predetermined quantile. Fixed and variable transaction costs are
both incorporated in the rebalancing decision. During every rebalancing
period, an investor rebalances if net portfolio return, taking into
account fixed and proportional transaction costs, is at least the
predetermined required return. The paper then uses four in-and-out-of-sample
windows to test the model for different levels of minimum required
returns (0, 5\%, and 10\%) and different quantile measures (1\%, 5\%,
10\% and 25\%). Based on the back-testing results, he concludes that
for a very risk-averse investor the best choice is to rebalance two
or three times in six months. On the other hand, a less risk-averse
investor should rebalance one time or not rebalance at all. 

These papers give us a starting point for incorporating rebalancing
into our model. We also incorporated t-copula joint distributions
and CVaR as a risk measure when rebalancing. 
\end{doublespace}

\begin{doublespace}

\section{Data}
\end{doublespace}

\begin{doublespace}
We used benchmark data obtained from the Duke University Management
Company (DUMAC). The data consisted of historical monthly returns
for the benchmarks representing seven asset classes: Morgan Stanley
Capital International (MSCI) All World (\$) for equity, Goldman Sachs
Commodity index (GSCI) for commodities, a blend of benchmarks  for
credit%
\footnote{1973-1984 Investment Grade Index, %
}, Barclays Capital U.S. Treasury Intermediate for interest rate, a
blend of benchmarks  for inflation sensitive%
\footnote{inflation blend%
}, National Association of Real Estate Investment Trusts (NaREIT) for
real estate, and Citi 3-month T-bills for cash. The benchmark return
data ranged from 1973 to 2009 and are all publicly available. We also
used the historical asset allocations of DUMAC as a reference.

