\end{doublespace}

\begin{doublespace}

\section{Methodology}
\end{doublespace}

\begin{doublespace}

\subsection{Arithmetic and Compounding Returns}
\end{doublespace}

\begin{doublespace}
We use two methods for calculating returns for a given time period.
In the arithmetic approach, returns from a period are added to returns
in the next period. In the compounding approach, returns from a period
are multiplied to the returns in the next period. Let $r_{t}$ be
the return during period $t$ and $V_{t}$ be the portfolio value
at the end of period $t$, we can express the two approaches as:

\begin{equation}
\text{Compounding: }V_{t+1}=V_{t}\cdot(1+r_{t+1})\end{equation}


\begin{equation}
\text{Arithmetic: }V_{t+1}=V_{t}+r_{r+1}.\end{equation}
The use of arithmetic returns is mathematically and computationally
convenient. Our initial analyses utilize arithmetic returns before
extending the mean-CVaR framework to consider compounding and rebalancing.
\end{doublespace}

\begin{doublespace}

\subsection{t-Copula}
\end{doublespace}

\begin{doublespace}
The historical return data of each individual asset class are first
fit to independent, marginal Generalized Pareto Distribution; this
GPD fit is piecewise so that a different function is fit to the lower
tail and upper tail to account for marginal distribution fat tails.
Next, independent marginal CDFs are transformed into their inverses,
creating a uniform distribution over {[}0, 1{]}. The historical returns
are then applied to their respective inverse CDF's to determine a
marginal probability of each return given the PDF. Using Maximum Likelihood,
a multivariate t-distribution fit is then constructed over these inverse
CDF historical probabilities to construct a t-copula that is identified
by a new correlation matrix and a single degree of freedom. 

The resulting t-Copula fit is centered at zero with characteristic
fat tails, similar to a standard normal distribution, and is used
for generating simulations. The multivariate t probability density
function is defined as follows:

\begin{equation}
f(x)=\frac{\Gamma(\frac{v+d}{2})}{\Gamma(\frac{v}{2})\sqrt{(\pi v)^{d}|\Sigma|}}(1+\frac{(x+\mu)'\Sigma^{-1}(x-\mu)}{v})^{-\frac{v+d}{2}}\end{equation}


\begin{equation}
\Gamma(x)=\int_{0}^{\inf}t^{x-1}e^{-t}dt\label{eq:Gamma function}\end{equation}
 where $d$ is the number of dimensions, $v$ is the degrees of freedom,
$\mu$ is the mean (zero, in this case), $\Sigma$ is the correlation
matrix, and $\Gamma$ is the gamma function as defined in Equation
\ref{eq:Gamma function}.
\end{doublespace}

\begin{doublespace}

\subsubsection{Generate Simulations}
\end{doublespace}

\begin{doublespace}
In order to simulate a certain number of months into the future, we
generate multiple single month returns for all asset classes. A single
month's return is simulated for all asset classes by generating multivariate
random numbers from the t-Copula fit and applying it to the following
formula:

\begin{equation}
\text{Simulated One Month Return}=\mu+\sigma\cdot\vec{x}\end{equation}


where $\mu$ is a vector of the historical monthly returns for each
asset class, $\sigma$ is a vector of the historical standard deviations
for each asset class, and $\vec{x}$ is a vector of the generated
multivariate t random numbers. We use the average historical, empirical
monthly returns and historical, empirical standard deviations of each
asset class in our research for consistency and objectiveness. When
simulations are drawn out of a t-copula, the likelihood of a market
crash scenario is an order of magnitude higher than that of a Gaussian
copula. 
\end{doublespace}

\begin{doublespace}

\subsection{Conditional Value at Risk (CVaR) }
\end{doublespace}

\begin{doublespace}
In order to calculate the CVaR of a certain portfolio over a set of
simulations, we sort the average returns of all the simulations from
lowest to highest and take the average of the lowest $\beta * Number of Simulation$
values.

\begin{equation}
\beta\text{-CVaR}=\frac{{1}}{(\beta\cdot n)}\sum_{i=1}^{\beta\cdot n}r_{i}\label{eq:CVaR calculation}\end{equation}
where $n$ is the number of simulations, $r_{i}$ is the i-th lowest
simulated return of an asset class, and $\beta$ is the desired CVaR
level (expressed as a percentage, e.g. 5\%). 
\end{doublespace}

\begin{doublespace}

\subsection{Analytical Mean-Variance Optimization}
\end{doublespace}

\begin{doublespace}
Markowitz (1952) pioneered the use of the normal mean-variance optimization
framework for maximizing portfolio returns and minimizing portfolio
risk (standard deviation). This framework analytically calculates
the optimal set of portfolio returns and variances using the historical
average return and historical standard deviation of each asset class
along with the historical covariance between each pair of asset classes.
Let $R$ be the fixed portfolio monthly return rate and $r_i$ the
average historical monthly return of each asset class. The optimization
problem can be expressed as follows:\begin{equation}
\min_{w_{1},w_{2},...w_{n}}\text{{\ensuremath{\sigma^{2}}}}(w_{1},w_{2},...,w_{n})\end{equation}


\begin{equation}
\sigma^{2}(w_{1},w_{2},...,w_{n})=\sum_{i=1}^{n}w_{i}^{2}\cdot\sigma_{i}^{2}+2\sum_{i=1}^{n}\sum_{j>i}^{n}w_{i}\cdot w_{j}\cdot\text{Cov(}i,j\text{) }\end{equation}

\end{doublespace}

\begin{equation}
\text{Cov(}i,j\text{)}=\sigma_{i}\cdot\sigma_{j}\cdot\rho_{ij}\end{equation}


\begin{doublespace}
\begin{equation}
w_{1},w_{2},...,w_{n}>0\end{equation}


\begin{equation}
w_{1}+w_{2}+...+w_{n}=1\end{equation}
\begin{equation}
\sum_{i=1}^{n}w_{i}\cdot r_{i}=R\end{equation}
The optimization uses multiple levels of $R$ between the lowest and
highest single asset class return (where the portfolio is 100\% weighted
in that single asset class) to determine the set of portfolios along
the efficient frontier. 
\end{doublespace}

\begin{doublespace}

\subsection{Single Period Simulated Mean-CVaR Optimization }
\end{doublespace}

\begin{doublespace}
The single period optimization of mean-CVaR minimizes CVaR at each
given level of return. The optimization calculates the CVaR as described
in Equation \ref{eq:CVaR calculation} while satisfying the condition
that the average return across all simulations is equal to the given
level of return we are optimizing on. Since this is a single period
optimization, arithmetic returns are used. 

Let $w_{i}$ denote the weight for asset class $i$, $R$ be the fixed
portfolio monthly return rate as defined before and $\tilde{R}$ be
the calculated portfolio monthly return rate at each run of the simulation.
We have the following optimization problem: 

\begin{equation}
\min_{w_{1},w_{2},...w_{n}}\text{{CVaR}}(w_{1},w_{2},...,w_{n})\end{equation}
\begin{equation}
w_{1},w_{2},...,w_{n}>0\end{equation}
\begin{equation}
w_{1}+w_{2}+...+w_{n}=1\end{equation}
\begin{equation}
\tilde{R}(w_{1},w_{2},...,w_{n})=R(w_{1},w_{2},...,w_{n})\end{equation}
\begin{equation}
V_{t}=V_{t}+\sum_{i=1}^{t}r_{i}\end{equation}


Our two linear constraints indicate that the weights must sum to one
and be nonnegative (since no borrowing is allowed). Since we want
to optimize on a fixed return, our nonlinear constraint is that our
average final portfolio return $\tilde{R}$ across all simulations
must be equivalent to the given fixed portfolio return $R$. 
\end{doublespace}

\begin{doublespace}

\subsection{Simulated Mean-CVaR Optimization with Compounding \label{sub:Simulated-Mean-CVaR-Optimization}}
\end{doublespace}

\begin{doublespace}
We adopt the compounding approach in this optimization. 

\begin{equation}
\min_{w_{1},w_{2},...w_{n}}\text{{CVaR}}(w_{1},w_{2},...,w_{n})\end{equation}
\begin{equation}
w_{1},w_{2},...,w_{n}>0\end{equation}
\begin{equation}
w_{1}+w_{2}+...+w_{n}=1\end{equation}
\begin{equation}
\tilde{R}(w_{1},w_{2},...,w_{n})=R(w_{1},w_{2},...,w_{n})\end{equation}


\begin{equation}
V_{t+1}=V_{t}\cdot(1+r_{t+1})\end{equation}


Our two linear constraints indicate that the weights must sum to one
and be nonnegative (since no borrowing is allowed). Since we want
to fix return, our nonlinear constraint is that our final portfolio
return $\tilde{R}$ must be the same as the given fixed portfolio
return $R$. 
\end{doublespace}

\begin{doublespace}

\subsection{Simulated Mean-CVaR Optimization with Rebalancing and Compounding}
\end{doublespace}

\begin{doublespace}
The implementation is the same as in Section \ref{sub:Simulated-Mean-CVaR-Optimization}
with one additional feature: every 12 months, we rebalance the portfolio
to the predetermined weights. We sum up the returns in that year and
we distribute the portfolio value according to a predetermined set
of weights and then compound it with future returns. Keeping all the
variables the same, and let $\vec{{V}_{t}^{'}}$ be the portfolio
vector after rebalancing. $\vec{{V}_{t}^{'}}$ contains the value
of each asset class at the end of time $t$. We have the following
nonlinear programming optimization problem:

\begin{equation}
\min_{w_{1},w_{2},...w_{n}}\text{{CVaR}}(w_{1},w_{2},...,w_{n})\end{equation}
\begin{equation}
w_{1},w_{2},...,w_{n}>0\end{equation}
\begin{equation}
w_{1}+w_{2}+...+w_{n}=1\end{equation}
\begin{equation}
\tilde{R}(w_{1},w_{2},...,w_{n})=R(w_{1},w_{2},...,w_{n})\end{equation}
\begin{equation}
V_{t+1}=V_{t}\cdot(1+r_{t+1})\end{equation}
\begin{equation}
\vec{{V}_{t}^{'}}=V_{t}\cdot(w_{1},w_{2},..,w_{n})\label{eq:constraint}\end{equation}


where the only addition is equation \ref{eq:constraint}. It specifies
that at each time period $t$, we redistribute the value of the portfolio
according to a predetermined vector of weights to obtain a portfolio
vector containing the values of each asset class.

Our objective function is to find the weights that will minimize CVaR.
CVaR is calculated analytically by trying out a set of asset weights
for all 5000 simulations. Each simulation gives a final portfolio
value, from which we can derive the monthly return rate by the formula: 

\begin{equation}
r=\frac{{V_{f}^{1/p}-1}}{b}\end{equation}
where $r$ is the monthly return rate, $V_{f}$ is the final portfolio
value, $p$ is the number of periods we simulate into the future,
and $b$ is number of months in between which we rebalance. A period
is the interval in which we rebalance once; it is equal to $b$ months.
For instance, suppose we start with a \$1 billion endowment and the
final portfolio value is \$24.62 billion. Suppose further that we
simulate 36 months into the future, rebalancing every 12 months. Then
our monthly return rate is $\frac{24.62^{1/3}-1}{12}=0.16$ monthly
return rate by the formula. For each set of weights, we carry out
5000 simulations, giving us 5000 monthly return rates. We take the
average of the lowest 5\%, or 250 final returns, to give us one CVaR.
Our objective is to find the minimum CVaR. We will keep trying weights
in an analytical fashion until we find the minimum CVaR. 
\end{doublespace}

